You know what!? That magnet paper would be actually very useful in diagnosis of the electric motor windings. For example you could take out the stator and check if the electromagnetic force is being produced by each winding. If the winding is dead shorted there will be no or very little electromagnetic force. Also, you could check if the relays are currently working. For example in a car, by turning on the ignition and checking if the relay is on or off using just the magnet paper (because the relay is an electromagnet and a ferromagnetic contact closed often in plastic body).

If you take a strong magnet you can wipe a refrigerator magnet so all the north (or south) fields point towards the refrigerator and it will no longer stick to a refrigerator. You can restore it by using a ruler and place it over the refrigerator magnet so it only covers the edge. Run the strong magnet over the refrigerator magnet using the ruler as a guide. Then move the ruler a few mm inwards, flip the strong magnet, and repeat. Keep doing this and you will restore the alternating fields on the refrigerator magnet and it will again stick to the refrigerator.

Without the magnetic film (which is also cool), you can take one of those refrigerator magnets with the stripes and carefully cut off one of the stripes with a pair of scissors. It works best with a rectangle. It's not an easy cut, due to how slim and long it is, but I have faith in you.
Then you can take that strip you removed, and hold it gently, and drag it across the stripes. The strip will bounce up and down, being attracted and repelled by each alternating stripe in the magnet.
It's pretty trippy the first time you see it (if you don't already know about the stripes, that is). I love to show this to physics majors and ask them if they can figure it out before I pull out the magnetic film. Often I'll tell them to listen first, before I tell them to look closely at the strip and then try it themselves.
